He's something to say about Big Daddy.

1230
01:12:41,640 --> 01:12:43,119
I want Brick.

1231
01:12:43,920 --> 01:12:45,751
He'll be down directly.

1232
01:12:45,960 --> 01:12:48,235
BlG MAMA: Sticky rain
always makes me sick.

1233
01:12:49,240 --> 01:12:51,800
Give me something
to wash this tablet down with.

1234
01:12:52,040 --> 01:12:54,998
BlG MAMA: What's wrong?
You've all got such long faces.

1235
01:12:57,800 --> 01:12:58,994
Big Mama needs you.

1236
01:12:59,200 --> 01:13:00,758
They'll tell her without me.

1237
01:13:00,880 --> 01:13:02,359
Please, Brick.

1238
01:13:02,560 --> 01:13:05,154
I just can't stand the way
that Mae and Gooper are--

1239
01:13:05,320 --> 01:13:07,754
What? Trying to grab this place
for themselves?

1240
01:13:07,960 --> 01:13:09,996
Let them have it all.

1241
01:13:10,200 --> 01:13:12,509
If you want to fight for a piece
of his carcass...

1242
01:13:12,600 --> 01:13:14,830
...you go ahead,
but you'll do it without me.

1243
01:13:14,920 --> 01:13:19,038
I deserved that. But not this time.
This time you're wrong.

1244
01:13:19,240 --> 01:13:20,593
What I can't stand is....

1245
01:13:20,680 --> 01:13:23,717
It's not losing this place, it's Big Mama.

1246
01:13:24,640 --> 01:13:27,359
I know what it's like
to lose somebody you love.

1247
01:13:27,560 --> 01:13:30,154
Careful, your claws are showing.

1248
01:13:33,320 --> 01:13:34,594
Close that door.

1249
01:13:34,800 --> 01:13:36,392
Don't close that door.

1250
01:13:37,320 --> 01:13:38,912
Let a little air circulate.

1251
01:13:39,600 --> 01:13:42,114
We shouldn't risk Big Daddy
hearing this discussion.

1252
01:13:42,520 --> 01:13:44,033
What discussion of what?

1253
01:13:44,120 --> 01:13:46,714
BlG MAMA: Maggie, Brick!
GOOPER: Now, now, Big Mama--

1254
01:13:46,800 --> 01:13:49,360
There won't be a word said
in Big Daddy's house...

1255
01:13:49,440 --> 01:13:52,398
...that he can't hear if he wants to.
Brick, where are you?

1256
01:13:52,480 --> 01:13:54,755
Where do you think?
Gone to pieces, that's where!

1257
01:13:54,960 --> 01:13:57,190
MAE: Doc, ain't there a cure for drinkers?

1258
01:13:57,400 --> 01:13:59,356
-He don't need no cure.
-Of course not.

1259
01:13:59,440 --> 01:14:02,113
GOOPER: He'll just drink
all the whisky in the state.

1260
01:14:02,200 --> 01:14:04,236
BlG MAMA: Stop that kind of talk!

1261
01:14:04,360 --> 01:14:07,909
Big Daddy takes a drink now and then.
I don't trust a man who don't drink.

1262
01:14:08,120 --> 01:14:09,553
Good for you!

1263
01:14:10,200 --> 01:14:12,794
Sit down and hold Big Mama's hand
while we talk.

1264
01:14:13,960 --> 01:14:16,190
BlG MAMA: What are you all
surrounding me for?

1265
01:14:16,400 --> 01:14:18,197
I don't need anyone to hold my hand.

1266
01:14:18,400 --> 01:14:19,310
Are you all crazy?

1267
01:14:19,400 --> 01:14:22,631
-You calm yourself, sweetheart.
-You calm yourself, Sister Woman!

1268
01:14:22,840 --> 01:14:24,114
How can I calm myself...

1269
01:14:24,200 --> 01:14:27,078
...with everyone staring at me
as if blood was on my face?

1270
01:14:29,000 --> 01:14:30,831
What's all this about?

1271
01:14:31,920 --> 01:14:33,035
Sit down, Mae.

1272
01:14:33,240 --> 01:14:35,993
Big Mama wants to know the truth
about the clinic report.

1273
01:14:36,200 --> 01:14:37,519
Truth!

1274
01:14:38,400 --> 01:14:40,960
Everybody keeps hollering about the truth.

1275
01:14:41,160 --> 01:14:42,559
The truth is as dirty...

1276
01:14:42,760 --> 01:14:43,829
...as lies!

1277
01:14:51,960 --> 01:14:53,791
Is there something I don't know, Doc?

1278
01:14:53,880 --> 01:14:55,279
DR. BAUGH: Well, lda....

1279
01:14:55,360 --> 01:14:56,634
I want to know!

1280
01:15:00,160 --> 01:15:03,118
-Somebody must be lying.
-Sit down, Mama, please.

1281
01:15:03,760 --> 01:15:05,478
I want to know about my husband.

1282
01:15:05,720 --> 01:15:09,235
He had the most thorough examination
at the Oppenheim Clinic.

1283
01:15:09,440 --> 01:15:11,396
One of the best clinics in the country.

1284
01:15:11,480 --> 01:15:13,948
The best in the country, bar none.

1285
01:15:14,120 --> 01:15:16,680
They were 99.9 percent sure
before they even started.

1286
01:15:16,920 --> 01:15:18,114
Right, Doc?

1287
01:15:18,240 --> 01:15:19,229
Sure of what?

1288
01:15:19,360 --> 01:15:21,476
MAGGlE: Not now!
MAE: The test was positive!

1289
01:15:21,560 --> 01:15:22,595
Mae, shut up.

1290
01:15:28,200 --> 01:15:31,272
It's hopeless. He knows it, too.

1291
01:15:32,240 --> 01:15:33,229
Hopeless?

1292
01:15:33,440 --> 01:15:36,000
MAE: Now, now, darling.
GOOPER: You had to know.

1293
01:15:37,160 --> 01:15:39,879
Why didn't they cut it out of him?

1294
01:15:41,160 --> 01:15:44,197
DR. BAUGH: It's gone past the knife.
MAE: He's dying, Big Mama.

1295
01:15:44,400 --> 01:15:46,470
You get away from me, Mae!

1296
01:15:46,680 --> 01:15:47,476
I want Brick.

1297
01:15:47,560 --> 01:15:49,551
Where's my Brick? Where's my only son?

1298
01:15:52,240 --> 01:15:53,229
Brick!

1299
01:15:53,440 --> 01:15:54,634
Mama, please.

1300
01:15:54,720 --> 01:15:55,709
[Big Mama sobs]

1301
01:15:55,840 --> 01:15:58,513
GOOPER: I'm your son, too.
MAE: Gooper's your firstborn.

1302
01:15:58,600 --> 01:16:00,636
GOOPER: Now, listen to me!
BlG MAMA: No!

1303
01:16:01,040 --> 01:16:02,917
-He'll be in pain.
-Gooper and I think--

1304
01:16:03,120 --> 01:16:04,473
GOOPER: Mae, shut up!

1305
01:16:04,680 --> 01:16:06,352
-Do you want to see him suffer?
-No.

1306
01:16:06,440 --> 01:16:08,829
Then he's got to be started on morphine.

1307
01:16:09,000 --> 01:16:11,560
Nobody's going to give
my husband morphine.

1308
01:16:11,840 --> 01:16:13,319
[Gasps repeatedly] No.

1309
01:16:18,640 --> 01:16:21,154
Why don't you give her a while
to adjust to the idea?

1310
01:16:21,240 --> 01:16:22,992
It's Maggie who's upsetting her.

1311
01:16:23,080 --> 01:16:27,073
GOOPER: lnstead of the needle, haven't
you got a pill to make the pain disappear?

1312
01:16:27,240 --> 01:16:30,676
Sometimes I wish I had a pill
to make people disappear.

1313
01:16:30,880 --> 01:16:34,031
GOOPER: Thanks for everything, Doc.
We sure do appreciate....

1314
01:16:34,120 --> 01:16:35,314
[Thunder rumbles]

1315
01:16:49,960 --> 01:16:50,756
Does Brick know?

1316
01:17:04,360 --> 01:17:06,191
You know, honey...

1317
01:17:08,080 --> 01:17:10,389
...we was never a very happy family.

1318
01:17:12,840 --> 01:17:15,115
There wasn't much joy in this house.

1319
01:17:15,320 --> 01:17:18,437
It wasn't Big Daddy's fault. It was just....

1320
01:17:18,920 --> 01:17:22,310
You know how some homes are happy.

1321
01:17:23,520 --> 01:17:27,877
I thought, coming home from the clinic
today, "Now we'll be happy here."

1322
01:17:28,480 --> 01:17:31,631
You and Brick will live with us
and have your children here.

1323
01:17:31,840 --> 01:17:33,956
And we'll help each other be happy.

1324
01:17:39,040 --> 01:17:40,951
Nothing's ever the way you plan, is it?

1325
01:17:47,600 --> 01:17:48,874
Margaret, honey...

1326
01:17:49,080 --> 01:17:50,354
...you've got to help Brick.

1327
01:17:50,440 --> 01:17:52,032
Make him pull himself together.

1328
01:17:52,240 --> 01:17:54,834
BlG MAMA: He'll take hold of things.
MAE: What things?

1329
01:17:57,400 --> 01:17:58,276
The place.

1330
01:17:58,760 --> 01:18:00,398
Big Mama, you've had a shock.

1331
01:18:00,600 --> 01:18:01,828
We've all had a shock.

1332
01:18:01,920 --> 01:18:04,753
-Let's be realistic.
-Big Daddy wouldn't be foolish enough--

1333
01:18:04,840 --> 01:18:07,957
He'd never put this place
in irresponsible hands!

1334
01:18:08,040 --> 01:18:10,349
He ain't putting this place
in anybody's hands.

1335
01:18:10,760 --> 01:18:13,035
My husband is not going to die!

1336
01:18:13,240 --> 01:18:15,549
I want you to get that in your heads.
Both of you.

1337
01:18:15,640 --> 01:18:17,995
-We're hoping too.
-We intend to pray for him.

1338
01:18:18,200 --> 01:18:20,191
I won't let you persuade Big Daddy to--

1339
01:18:20,280 --> 01:18:22,191
Gooper is your firstborn!

1340
01:18:22,400 --> 01:18:25,949
He's always had to carry a bigger load
of the responsibilities than Brick.

1341
01:18:26,040 --> 01:18:29,669
Brick never carried a thing in his life
but a football or a highball.

1342
01:18:29,880 --> 01:18:31,598
GOOPER: Will you let me talk, please?

1343
01:18:31,680 --> 01:18:33,079
Yes, of course.

1344
01:18:34,520 --> 01:18:37,273
A 28,000 acre plantation
is a mighty big thing to run.

1345
01:18:37,480 --> 01:18:38,833
Almost single-handed.

1346
01:18:39,040 --> 01:18:42,430
You had your law practice in Memphis.
When did you run this place?

1347
01:18:42,600 --> 01:18:45,034
Mama, let's be fair.

1348
01:18:45,720 --> 01:18:47,950
Ever since Big Daddy's health
started failing...

1349
01:18:48,040 --> 01:18:50,429
...Gooper's worked like a fool
to keep this place up.

1350
01:18:50,520 --> 01:18:51,316
Mae....

1351
01:18:51,400 --> 01:18:53,834
Gooper won't admit it.
He never thought of it as a duty.

1352
01:18:53,920 --> 01:18:54,750
Mae!

1353
01:18:55,040 --> 01:18:56,553
Big Daddy don't know what he owns.

1354
01:18:56,640 --> 01:19:00,553
GOOPER: The point is I won't see this
place ruined by a drunken ex-football hero.

1355
01:19:00,760 --> 01:19:02,512
Shut up about my husband!

1356
01:19:02,720 --> 01:19:03,516
You shut up!

1357
01:19:03,600 --> 01:19:05,477
He has no right to slander--

1358
01:19:05,680 --> 01:19:08,240
I can discuss my brother
with my family members...

1359
01:19:08,680 --> 01:19:10,875
...which don't include you!

1360
01:19:11,960 --> 01:19:14,190
GOOPER: Why not go up
and drink with Brick?

1361
01:19:14,280 --> 01:19:16,714
MAE: If the hero hadn't passed out already.

1362
01:19:16,920 --> 01:19:19,639
GOOPER: He may have to pass up
the Sugar Bowl this year.

1363
01:19:19,720 --> 01:19:21,836
Or was it the Rose Bowl
he made his run in?

1364
01:19:21,920 --> 01:19:23,512
It was the punch bowl, honey.

1365
01:19:23,600 --> 01:19:25,556
The cut-glass punch bowl.

1366
01:19:26,080 --> 01:19:28,071
I always get that boy's bowls mixed up.

1367
01:19:28,680 --> 01:19:32,116
I have never seen such malice
toward a brother.

1368
01:19:32,320 --> 01:19:34,436
What about his malice toward Gooper?

1369
01:19:34,640 --> 01:19:37,916
GOOPER: He can't even stand being
in the same room with me.

1370
01:19:39,320 --> 01:19:41,117
LACEY: Can I help you, Mr. Brick?

1371
01:19:41,200 --> 01:19:42,428
No, thank you, Lacey.

1372
01:19:42,520 --> 01:19:45,080
BRlCK: Where's my father?
LACEY: He's in the cellar.

1373
01:19:45,280 --> 01:19:47,077
And he's alone.

1374
01:19:47,440 --> 01:19:48,555
And he's....

1375
01:19:49,240 --> 01:19:50,798
Thank you, Lacey.

1376
01:19:51,280 --> 01:19:53,350
It's a deliberate campaign to ruin Brick.

1377
01:19:53,440 --> 01:19:54,759
MAE: He don't need help.

1378
01:19:54,840 --> 01:19:57,195
For the most disgusting,
sordid reasons on earth.

1379
01:19:57,400 --> 01:19:58,310
Avarice.

1380
01:19:58,520 --> 01:20:00,909
Avarice and greed!

1381
01:20:01,120 --> 01:20:01,996
No, Margaret.

1382
01:20:02,200 --> 01:20:03,519
Don't cry.

1383
01:20:03,720 --> 01:20:05,950
-That takes the cake!
-Mae.

1384
01:20:06,160 --> 01:20:07,832
Who are the tears for?

1385
01:20:08,680 --> 01:20:09,510
MAE: Brick?

1386
01:20:09,600 --> 01:20:10,635
Big Daddy?

1387
01:20:10,720 --> 01:20:11,789
-Or for yourself?
-Mae!

1388
01:20:12,120 --> 01:20:13,951
Are you crying 'cause you're childless?

1389
01:20:14,040 --> 01:20:15,598
You know why she's got no kids?

1390
01:20:15,800 --> 01:20:18,997
MAE: Ask her big, beautiful husband.
GOOPER: Mae!

1391
01:20:19,800 --> 01:20:22,394
You just won't let me do this
the nice way, will you?

1392
01:20:24,320 --> 01:20:26,515
You always said I never loved Big Daddy.

1393
01:20:26,720 --> 01:20:28,153
How would you know?

1394
01:20:29,440 --> 01:20:30,668
How would he know?

1395
01:20:30,800 --> 01:20:32,677
Did he ever let anyone love him?

1396
01:20:32,880 --> 01:20:35,348
It was always Brick.
From the day he was born...

1397
01:20:35,440 --> 01:20:37,954
...he was always partial to Brick. Why?

1398
01:20:38,120 --> 01:20:40,680
Big Daddy wanted me to become a lawyer.
I did.

1399
01:20:40,880 --> 01:20:42,199
He said get married. I did.

1400
01:20:42,400 --> 01:20:44,118
He said have kids. I did.

1401
01:20:44,320 --> 01:20:46,276
He said live in Memphis. I did.

1402
01:20:46,480 --> 01:20:48,994
Whatever he said to do, I did.

1403
01:20:50,200 --> 01:20:52,760
I don't give a damn
whether Big Daddy likes me...

1404
01:20:52,960 --> 01:20:54,518
...or did or never did...

1405
01:20:54,720 --> 01:20:56,756
...or will or will never.

1406
01:20:58,040 --> 01:21:01,430
I've appealed for common decency
and fair play.

1407
01:21:01,640 --> 01:21:03,278
Now I'm telling you!

1408
01:21:03,600 --> 01:21:05,477
I intend to protect my interests.

1409
01:21:05,640 --> 01:21:08,200
I'm not a corporation lawyer for nothing.

1410
01:21:08,880 --> 01:21:11,633
GOOPER: Go get my briefcase.
MAE: Yes, honey.

1411
01:21:17,440 --> 01:21:18,998
It was....

1412
01:21:19,240 --> 01:21:21,834
It was the Cotton Bowl, Sister Woman.

1413
01:21:27,840 --> 01:21:30,832
[Lively instrumental music
plays on phonograph]

1414
01:21:40,680 --> 01:21:41,795
Pa?

1415
01:22:03,440 --> 01:22:04,919
[Big Daddy moans]

1416
01:22:07,440 --> 01:22:08,509
Pa?

1417
01:22:21,000 --> 01:22:23,958
BRlCK: Give me your hand.
BlG DADDY: I don't want your hand!

1418
01:22:27,040 --> 01:22:29,031
[Big Daddy gasps for breath]

1419
01:23:15,280 --> 01:23:16,235
No.

1420
01:23:16,440 --> 01:23:17,793
It's my pain.

1421
01:23:17,960 --> 01:23:19,712
That makes it my business.

1422
01:23:20,040 --> 01:23:22,793
I thought you went and hid yourself.
What do you want?

1423
01:23:23,040 --> 01:23:24,996
I came to apologize.

1424
01:23:26,440 --> 01:23:28,112
What for, telling me the truth?

1425
01:23:28,320 --> 01:23:31,517
-There must a dozen reasons.
-Save them.

1426
01:23:31,720 --> 01:23:34,234
I hate apologies. Especially for the truth.

1427
01:23:34,440 --> 01:23:37,398
Whatever you did, don't apologize.
Just don't do it again.

1428
01:23:37,600 --> 01:23:39,591
If you didn't do it, start doing it.

1429
01:23:39,800 --> 01:23:41,791
Start by getting me a cigar
out of that coat.

1430
01:23:41,880 --> 01:23:44,394
-You think you ought to--
-Get me the cigar, boy!

1431
01:23:50,080 --> 01:23:51,069
It's wet from rain.

1432
01:23:51,160 --> 01:23:55,039
You're all wet yourself.
It's a lousy joke, but it's true.

1433
01:23:58,760 --> 01:24:00,671
Modern science!

1434
01:24:12,680 --> 01:24:14,159
Get me that...

1435
01:24:18,480 --> 01:24:19,310
...that robe.

1436
01:24:30,720 --> 01:24:33,632
-There's a bottle in that desk.
-I don't want a drink.

1437
01:24:33,840 --> 01:24:35,239
I do.

1438
01:24:35,400 --> 01:24:36,992
I want a drink.

1439
01:24:37,480 --> 01:24:40,040
I've got a million clicks in my guts.

1440
01:24:41,320 --> 01:24:43,709
Knives sharpening themselves.

1441
01:24:46,600 --> 01:24:48,716
BlG DADDY: You know about clicks,
don't you?

1442
01:24:51,800 --> 01:24:54,030
So you bought me a birthday present, huh?

1443
01:24:55,320 --> 01:24:57,038
No, Maggie bought it.

1444
01:24:58,200 --> 01:25:01,795
BlG DADDY: She's got good taste that girl.
BRlCK: In some things, yes...

1445
01:25:02,000 --> 01:25:03,672
...but not in men.

1446
01:25:06,480 --> 01:25:08,038
Nice soft material.

1447
01:25:08,440 --> 01:25:10,317
This is my soft birthday.

1448
01:25:10,520 --> 01:25:13,751
Not my gold or silver.
This is my soft birthday.

1449
01:25:18,760 --> 01:25:20,352
Here's to my...

1450
01:25:20,520 --> 01:25:22,272
...Iast birthday.

1451
01:25:23,560 --> 01:25:25,551
Aren't you drinking to that?

1452
01:25:27,720 --> 01:25:29,312
Clickety-click.

1453
01:25:40,320 --> 01:25:42,470
You know what I'm going to do
before I die?

1454
01:25:43,720 --> 01:25:45,790
I'm going to open up all these boxes.

1455
01:25:48,040 --> 01:25:49,632
Will you look at this stuff?

1456
01:25:50,200 --> 01:25:51,315
Bought most of it...

1457
01:25:51,520 --> 01:25:54,034
...when I took your mother to Europe
on that tour.

1458
01:25:54,120 --> 01:25:56,839
Never had such a lousy time in my life.

1459
01:25:57,160 --> 01:25:59,879
That Europe is nothing
but a great big auction.

1460
01:26:00,160 --> 01:26:03,709
Bunch of old worn-out places.
It's just a big fire sale.

1461
01:26:03,920 --> 01:26:05,911
Big Mama went wild in it.

1462
01:26:06,120 --> 01:26:08,680
She just bought and bought.

1463
01:26:09,400 --> 01:26:12,278
She was lucky I'm a rich man.
Yes, it sure is lucky.

1464
01:26:13,040 --> 01:26:16,032
Got any idea what I'm worth? Ask Gooper.

1465
01:26:16,240 --> 01:26:18,834
He knows to the penny
unless I miss my guess.

1466
01:26:20,200 --> 01:26:23,715
Close on $10 million in cash
and blue-chip stocks...

1467
01:26:23,920 --> 01:26:26,639
...besides some 28,000 acres
of the richest land...

1468
01:26:26,840 --> 01:26:28,592
...this side of the Valley Nile.

1469
01:26:28,800 --> 01:26:30,916
That is pretty rich to be.

1470
01:26:33,600 --> 01:26:38,196
There's one thing you can't buy
in a Europe fire sale...

1471
01:26:38,720 --> 01:26:40,870
...or any other market on earth.

1472
01:26:41,480 --> 01:26:43,038
That's your life.

1473
01:26:45,600 --> 01:26:48,433
You can't buy back your life
when it's finished.

1474
01:26:48,680 --> 01:26:50,477
No, sir. Nobody can do that.

1475
01:26:52,120 --> 01:26:53,519
Feeling sorry for me or you?

1476
01:26:57,960 --> 01:26:58,915
For you, Papa.

1477
01:26:59,080 --> 01:27:01,640
That's good,
because you're going to miss me.

1478
01:27:03,680 --> 01:27:06,114
Why did you let Ma buy all this stuff?

1479
01:27:06,760 --> 01:27:10,548
The human animal is a beast
that eventually has to die.

1480
01:27:10,920 --> 01:27:14,196
If he's got money, he buys and he buys.

1481
01:27:15,080 --> 01:27:17,799
The reason why he buys everything he can,
is because...

1482
01:27:17,880 --> 01:27:21,714
...of a crazy hope that one of the things
he buys will be life everlasting...

1483
01:27:22,280 --> 01:27:24,111
...which it never can be.

1484
01:27:24,520 --> 01:27:28,115
I've suddenly noticed you don't call me
Big Daddy anymore.

1485
01:27:28,320 --> 01:27:31,198
If you needed a Big Daddy,
why didn't you come to me?

1486
01:27:31,400 --> 01:27:35,234
If you wanted someone to lean on, why
Skipper? Why not me? I'm your father.

1487
01:27:35,520 --> 01:27:38,193
You should've come to your kinfolk.
Those who love you.

1488
01:27:38,280 --> 01:27:41,556
You don't know what love means.
To you it's another four-letter word.

1489
01:27:41,640 --> 01:27:43,119
You've got a short memory.

1490
01:27:43,400 --> 01:27:47,109
-What did you want that I didn't buy?
-You can't buy love!

1491
01:27:47,320 --> 01:27:50,551
You bought $1 million worth of junk!
Does it love you?

1492
01:27:50,760 --> 01:27:53,991
Who do you think I bought it for?
It's yours, the place, the money!

1493
01:27:54,200 --> 01:27:56,077
I don't want things!

1494
01:27:58,520 --> 01:28:00,158
We drew this up--

1495
01:28:00,240 --> 01:28:01,639
[Crashing]

1496
01:28:02,280 --> 01:28:05,590
-We drew this up with the advice--
-Get out of the way.

1497
01:28:07,400 --> 01:28:09,630
-Get out of my way.
-We're settling this first.

1498
01:28:09,720 --> 01:28:12,712
-I don't want to see it.
-It's a sort of a plan. A preliminary.

1499
01:28:15,520 --> 01:28:17,511
[Crashing and breaking glass]

1500
01:28:20,200 --> 01:28:21,679
Waste!

1501
01:28:31,240 --> 01:28:32,593
Worthless!

1502
01:28:41,160 --> 01:28:42,593
Worthless!

1503
01:28:50,440 --> 01:28:52,112
[Brick sobs]

1504
01:29:03,680 --> 01:29:04,715
Don't, son.

1505
01:29:06,280 --> 01:29:07,713
Please don't cry.

1506
01:29:21,960 --> 01:29:23,393
BlG DADDY: That's funny.

1507
01:29:24,000 --> 01:29:27,436
I never saw you cry before.
Did you ever cry as a kid?

1508
01:29:27,520 --> 01:29:31,877
Can't you understand?
I never wanted your place or money.

1509
01:29:32,160 --> 01:29:34,276
I don't want to own anything!

1510
01:29:34,480 --> 01:29:37,631
All I wanted was a father, not a boss!

1511
01:29:38,120 --> 01:29:40,156
I wanted you to love me.

1512
01:29:40,360 --> 01:29:41,839
I did and I do.

1513
01:29:42,880 --> 01:29:45,314
Not me and not Gooper,
and not even Mama.

1514
01:29:45,480 --> 01:29:46,799
That's a lie.

1515
01:29:47,000 --> 01:29:48,433
I loved her. I gave her--

1516
01:29:48,640 --> 01:29:51,598
Things, Papa, you gave her things.

1517
01:29:51,800 --> 01:29:54,234
A house, a trip to Europe, all this junk.

1518
01:29:54,440 --> 01:29:57,910
Some jewelry.
You gave her things, not love.

1519
01:29:59,560 --> 01:30:01,357
I gave her an empire.

1520
01:30:01,560 --> 01:30:04,358
I've seen you out there on your empire...

1521
01:30:04,560 --> 01:30:07,597
...with the men who run it for you.
You don't know their names...

1522
01:30:07,800 --> 01:30:11,270
...or if they've kids or are happy.
You've never looked into their faces.

1523
01:30:11,360 --> 01:30:14,830
What are faces? You don't build an empire
by remembering faces.

1524
01:30:15,080 --> 01:30:17,958
Next week,
I'll start building that textile plant.

1525
01:30:18,160 --> 01:30:21,948
I'll not only grow my own cotton,
I'll weave it and market it.

1526
01:30:22,120 --> 01:30:22,836
I'll tell you...

1527
01:30:23,040 --> 01:30:25,349
...in a year or two from now--

1528
01:30:40,440 --> 01:30:44,513
The men who build empires die,
and empires die too.

1529
01:30:45,160 --> 01:30:46,388
No, it won't.

1530
01:30:46,600 --> 01:30:48,511
That's why I've got you and Gooper.

1531
01:30:48,720 --> 01:30:49,914
Look at Gooper.

1532
01:30:50,120 --> 01:30:53,351
Look at what he's become.
Is that what you wanted him to be?

1533
01:30:53,560 --> 01:30:54,993
Look at me.

1534
01:30:55,320 --> 01:30:59,359
You were right. I am a 30-year-old kid.
And pretty soon I'll be a 50-year-old kid.

1535
01:30:59,560 --> 01:31:02,757
I don't know what to believe in.
What's the good of living?

1536
01:31:02,960 --> 01:31:06,350
There's got to be some purpose in life,
some meaning.

1537
01:31:06,960 --> 01:31:10,430
Look at me, for the sake of God,
before it's too late!

1538
01:31:10,600 --> 01:31:13,353
For once, look at me as I really am.

1539
01:31:13,560 --> 01:31:14,788
Look at me!

1540
01:31:16,200 --> 01:31:17,713
I'm a failure. I'm a drunk.

1541
01:31:17,840 --> 01:31:21,310
On my own in the open market,
I'm not worth the price of a decent burial.

1542
01:31:21,520 --> 01:31:25,877
-All of you blame me for everything, huh?
-No, Papa.

1543
01:31:29,240 --> 01:31:32,152
We've known each other all my life
and we're strangers.

1544
01:31:32,760 --> 01:31:37,117
You own 28,000 acres.
You own $1 0 million.

1545
01:31:37,320 --> 01:31:41,518
You own a wife and two children.
You own us, but you don't love us.

1546
01:31:42,480 --> 01:31:44,948
-ln my own way--
-No, sir.

1547
01:31:45,360 --> 01:31:47,351
You don't even like people.

1548
01:31:48,280 --> 01:31:51,477
You wanted Gooper and me to have kids.
Why?

1549
01:31:52,600 --> 01:31:56,479
I want a part of me to keep living.
I won't have it end with the grave.

1550
01:31:56,680 --> 01:31:57,829
Look!

1551
01:31:58,440 --> 01:32:00,874
This is what my father left me.

1552
01:32:01,080 --> 01:32:02,513
This lousy old suitcase!

1553
01:32:03,200 --> 01:32:05,395
On the inside was nothing...

1554
01:32:05,600 --> 01:32:09,149
...but his uniform
from the Spanish-American War.

1555
01:32:09,360 --> 01:32:11,590
This was his legacy to me.

1556
01:32:11,800 --> 01:32:13,392
Nothing at all!

1557
01:32:15,400 --> 01:32:18,198
And I built this place from nothing.

1558
01:32:19,040 --> 01:32:21,031
[Slow instrumental music]

1559
01:32:23,040 --> 01:32:25,110
And that's all he left you?

1560
01:32:25,480 --> 01:32:27,914
Yeah, he was a hobo.

1561
01:32:29,480 --> 01:32:32,233
Best-known tramp on the boxcar circuit.

1562
01:32:32,440 --> 01:32:35,830
He worked once in a while as a field hand.
I'd tag along.

1563
01:32:36,440 --> 01:32:39,716
Sat on my bare bottom, in the dirt,
waiting for him.

1564
01:32:41,160 --> 01:32:42,832
Outside of hunger...

1565
01:32:43,040 --> 01:32:45,395
...first thing I could remember is shame.

1566
01:32:45,600 --> 01:32:48,319
I was ashamed
of that miserable, old tramp.

1567
01:32:48,760 --> 01:32:52,912
I was riding boxcars when I was nine,
something you never had to do.

1568
01:32:53,120 --> 01:32:56,351
And you'll never have to bury me
like I did him.

1569
01:32:57,040 --> 01:33:00,191
I buried him in a meadow,
alongside a railroad track.

1570
01:33:00,360 --> 01:33:03,636
We were running to catch a freight
and his heart gave out.

1571
01:33:06,560 --> 01:33:07,959
You know something?

1572
01:33:09,240 --> 01:33:11,356
That lousy old tramp died laughing.

1573
01:33:11,560 --> 01:33:13,152
BRlCK: Laughing at what?

1574
01:33:14,120 --> 01:33:15,917
Himself, I guess.

1575
01:33:16,120 --> 01:33:17,519
A hobo tramp...

1576
01:33:17,720 --> 01:33:21,429
...not a nickel in his jeans.
No future, no past.

1577
01:33:22,920 --> 01:33:26,595
Or maybe he was laughing
because he was happy.

1578
01:33:27,480 --> 01:33:29,311
Happy at having you with him.

1579
01:33:29,480 --> 01:33:32,199
He took you everywhere
and he kept you with him.

1580
01:33:33,960 --> 01:33:35,837
I don't want to talk about that.

1581
01:33:50,600 --> 01:33:52,318
Yeah, I loved him.

1582
01:33:56,200 --> 01:33:58,998
I reckon I never loved anything
as much as that...

1583
01:33:59,200 --> 01:34:00,838
...Iousy old tramp.

1584
01:34:02,600 --> 01:34:03,953
BRlCK: And you say...

1585
01:34:04,160 --> 01:34:06,469
...he left you nothing but a suitcase...

1586
01:34:06,680 --> 01:34:10,036
...with a uniform in it
from the Spanish-American War?

1587
01:34:10,560 --> 01:34:12,198
And some memories.

1588
01:34:13,480 --> 01:34:14,674
And love.

1589
01:34:20,320 --> 01:34:22,595
Did I tell you all them stories
about my old man?

1590
01:34:22,800 --> 01:34:24,313
About fifty times.

1591
01:34:32,840 --> 01:34:35,308
[Big Daddy moans and screams]

1592
01:34:37,960 --> 01:34:41,316
It's a plan to protect the Delta's
biggest estate from irresponsibility.

1593
01:34:41,400 --> 01:34:42,355
You have to sign.

1594
01:34:42,480 --> 01:34:43,959
[Big Daddy screams]

1595
01:34:45,480 --> 01:34:47,198
BlG MAMA: Where is it?

1596
01:34:48,040 --> 01:34:48,677
What?

1597
01:34:48,800 --> 01:34:51,997
What the doctor left
to make his pain easier.

1598
01:34:52,640 --> 01:34:56,189
Brick's down there with him.
He'll help Big Daddy.

1599
01:34:56,400 --> 01:34:57,799
MAE: Help him? How?

1600
01:34:58,000 --> 01:34:59,991
-By running the 100-yard dash?
-Shut up.

1601
01:35:00,200 --> 01:35:03,112
MAE: Maybe he'll cheer him up
by kicking some field goals.

1602
01:35:03,400 --> 01:35:06,119
One more crack, Queenie...

1603
01:35:06,280 --> 01:35:10,512
...and I will not only spit in your eye
but I will punch it black and blue.

1604
01:35:10,600 --> 01:35:11,430
Hold on a minute!

1605
01:35:11,520 --> 01:35:14,034
-I'm not listening to any more--
-Mae was only saying--

1606
01:35:14,120 --> 01:35:16,759
I know what she said,
and I know exactly what she meant.

1607
01:35:16,840 --> 01:35:18,637
The only world that Brick knows--

1608
01:35:18,720 --> 01:35:20,870
MAGGlE: It's not a world he made.

1609
01:35:25,000 --> 01:35:25,876
Ladies!

1610
01:35:27,720 --> 01:35:30,075
-No.
-Why won't you take it?

1611
01:35:31,040 --> 01:35:34,237
-lt'll kill the pain, that's all.
-lt'll kill the senses, too.

1612
01:35:34,440 --> 01:35:37,079
When you've got pain
at least you know you're alive.

1613
01:35:42,920 --> 01:35:44,638
It's easing somewhat now.

1614
01:35:44,800 --> 01:35:46,791
[Slow instrumental music]

1615
01:35:46,960 --> 01:35:48,439
When you've got pain...

1616
01:35:48,840 --> 01:35:51,752
...it's better to judge yourself,
a lot of things.

1617
01:35:51,960 --> 01:35:54,349
I'm not going to stupefy myself
with that stuff.

1618
01:35:54,440 --> 01:35:56,032
I want to think clear.

1619
01:35:56,240 --> 01:35:58,629
I want to see everything
and feel everything.

1620
01:35:58,840 --> 01:36:00,512
Then I won't mind going.

1621
01:36:01,640 --> 01:36:03,710
I've got the guts to die.

1622
01:36:03,920 --> 01:36:06,753
What I want to know is,
have you got the guts to live?

1623
01:36:07,120 --> 01:36:08,519
BRlCK: I don't know.

1624
01:36:09,800 --> 01:36:11,279
BlG DADDY: We can try.

1625
01:36:13,120 --> 01:36:16,032
We could start by helping each other
up these stairs.

1626
01:36:28,040 --> 01:36:29,189
Yes, sir.

1627
01:36:32,240 --> 01:36:33,719
GOOPER: At least read them.

1628
01:36:33,840 --> 01:36:35,990
Put those papers away
before I tear them up.

1629
01:36:36,200 --> 01:36:38,350
I don't want to know what's in them.

1630
01:36:38,560 --> 01:36:42,838
I'm talking in Big Daddy's language.
I'm his wife, not his widow. His wife!

1631
01:36:43,200 --> 01:36:45,475
-What I've got here--
-He said it's just a plan.

1632
01:36:45,560 --> 01:36:48,438
Plan basis. What I'll say to your plan is....

1633
01:36:50,400 --> 01:36:53,915
Maggie, what is it Big Daddy says
when he's disgusted?

1634
01:36:54,000 --> 01:36:56,833
He says "bull" when he's disgusted.

1635
01:36:57,000 --> 01:36:59,594
That's right. I say "bull" like Big Daddy.

1636
01:36:59,800 --> 01:37:02,553
-Coarse language don't seem called for.
-Bull!

1637
01:37:02,640 --> 01:37:04,676
GOOPER: I'm outraged by this kind of talk.

1638
01:37:04,760 --> 01:37:08,355
BlG MAMA: Then stop talking like
your father's dead and me along with him.

1639
01:37:08,440 --> 01:37:10,590
What about her? She wants her share, too.

1640
01:37:11,000 --> 01:37:13,070
As far as Brick is concerned...

1641
01:37:13,280 --> 01:37:15,714
...nobody's going to take nothing.

1642
01:37:15,920 --> 01:37:17,558
Not till Big Daddy lets go...

1643
01:37:17,760 --> 01:37:21,639
...and maybe just possibly, not even then!

1644
01:37:21,960 --> 01:37:23,871
MAGGlE: No, Mama, not even then.

1645
01:37:27,880 --> 01:37:29,598
BlG DADDY: Hello, Bucky!

1646
01:37:32,360 --> 01:37:35,079
Looks like the wind took some liberties
with this place.

1647
01:37:35,240 --> 01:37:36,912
-Evening, Cap'n!
-Evening, Cap'n!

1648
01:37:37,000 --> 01:37:39,594
-Storm cross over the river?
-Gone to Arkansas.

1649
01:37:39,800 --> 01:37:41,472
Rain do some good, Cap'n?

1650
01:37:41,640 --> 01:37:43,232
Some good, I reckon.

1651
01:37:45,160 --> 01:37:46,388
Some good.

1652
01:37:47,240 --> 01:37:48,878
GOOPER: You could at least read them.

1653
01:37:48,960 --> 01:37:52,589
BlG MAMA: Put them away before I tear
them up. I don't know what's in them.

1654
01:37:52,680 --> 01:37:54,113
I don't want to know.

1655
01:37:55,640 --> 01:37:56,834
Can I come in?

1656
01:37:58,640 --> 01:38:01,234
Has the storm done any damage?

1657
01:38:01,440 --> 01:38:03,954
Which storm are you talking about?
The one outside...

1658
01:38:04,040 --> 01:38:05,951
...or that hullabaloo going on in here?

1659
01:38:14,320 --> 01:38:15,435
Excuse me, sir.

1660
01:38:15,760 --> 01:38:20,072
Heard some mighty loud talking.
What's the powwow about?

1661
01:38:20,440 --> 01:38:23,352
MAE: Nothing, Big Daddy. Nothing at all.

1662
01:38:23,840 --> 01:38:26,832
What's in them important-looking
documents you've got there?

1663
01:38:27,240 --> 01:38:29,800
GOOPER: Nothing.
Nothing much of anything at all.

1664
01:38:30,080 --> 01:38:34,437
BlG DADDY: Then why are you and Sister
Woman scurrying and scrounging around?

1665
01:38:35,040 --> 01:38:37,474
Looks like a whole lot of nothing to me.

1666
01:38:40,640 --> 01:38:42,676
What's that smell in this room?

1667
01:38:43,480 --> 01:38:45,152
Didn't you notice it, Brick?

1668
01:38:45,800 --> 01:38:49,429
Didn't you notice the powerful
and obnoxious odor of mendacity?

1669
01:38:52,840 --> 01:38:55,308
Yes, sir, I think I did.

1670
01:38:55,520 --> 01:38:58,751
Ain't nothing more powerful
than the odor of mendacity.

1671
01:38:59,840 --> 01:39:02,195
-Didn't you notice it, Gooper?
-What, sir?

1672
01:39:02,440 --> 01:39:04,396
What about you, Sister Woman?

1673
01:39:04,600 --> 01:39:08,115
Didn't you notice an unpleasant smell
of mendacity in this room?

1674
01:39:08,600 --> 01:39:10,795
I don't even know what that is.

1675
01:39:11,000 --> 01:39:14,436
You can smell it. It smells like death.

1676
01:39:14,600 --> 01:39:16,477
[Big Mama whimpers]

1677
01:39:18,960 --> 01:39:21,190
BlG DADDY: What's the matter
with that woman?

1678
01:39:21,280 --> 01:39:22,952
What's-your-name, what's wrong?

1679
01:39:23,120 --> 01:39:25,918
She just had a slight dizzy spell.

1680
01:39:26,120 --> 01:39:28,429
You'd better watch that.
A stroke's a bad way to go.

1681
01:39:31,120 --> 01:39:34,635
Look, he's wearing
Brick's birthday present.

1682
01:39:35,800 --> 01:39:39,236
I haven't given you my present yet
but I will now.

1683
01:39:39,560 --> 01:39:41,232
I have an announcement.

1684
01:39:41,440 --> 01:39:43,192
What kind of an announcement?

1685
01:39:44,600 --> 01:39:46,716
An announcement of life beginning.

1686
01:39:49,160 --> 01:39:50,991
A child is coming...

1687
01:39:52,040 --> 01:39:54,474
...sired by Brick out of Maggie the cat.

1688
01:39:58,280 --> 01:40:00,475
I have Brick's child in my body.

1689
01:40:01,320 --> 01:40:03,276
And that is my present to you.

1690
01:40:03,720 --> 01:40:07,349
Did you ever in your born days
hear such a bald-faced lie?

1691
01:40:07,560 --> 01:40:08,675
Shut up.

1692
01:40:10,440 --> 01:40:11,759
Thank you.

1693
01:40:11,960 --> 01:40:13,678
Thank you very much.

1694
01:40:26,600 --> 01:40:30,229
Yes, indeed, this girl has life in her body.

1695
01:40:31,240 --> 01:40:32,832
And that's no lie.

1696
01:40:33,760 --> 01:40:37,036
I want my lawyer in the morning.
My lawyer!

1697
01:40:38,600 --> 01:40:40,636
-Brick?
-Yes, Big Daddy?

1698
01:40:43,280 --> 01:40:46,192
I'm going out to look this place over
before I give it up.

1699
01:40:46,680 --> 01:40:48,716
The place and the people on it.

1700
01:40:51,040 --> 01:40:52,234
Ida?

1701
01:40:54,720 --> 01:40:56,119
You want to come with me?

1702
01:41:04,840 --> 01:41:06,239
GOOPER: Brick....

1703
01:41:09,480 --> 01:41:11,596
What were you two talking about
down there?

1704
01:41:11,680 --> 01:41:12,556
Us.

1705
01:41:12,960 --> 01:41:14,075
Me, too?

1706
01:41:14,920 --> 01:41:15,557
Yeah.

1707
01:41:15,760 --> 01:41:18,399
You ripped your own brother apart.

1708
01:41:19,680 --> 01:41:21,272
Do you believe that, Gooper?

1709
01:41:25,280 --> 01:41:26,679
-No.
-Well, I do!

1710
01:41:26,880 --> 01:41:27,790
Keep still.

1711
01:41:28,000 --> 01:41:32,118
A family crisis brings out the best
and the worst in every member.

1712
01:41:32,440 --> 01:41:33,839
That's the truth.

1713
